According the possible solution No. 2:
It seems that it's actually enough to add an underscore as a prefix.

> Element names must start with a letter or underscore
> [XML Naming Rules](http://www.w3schools.com/xml/xml_elements.asp)

issue.title: Change "sessions" API view to not use tokens' names as XML element names

repository.name: zaproxy
repository.description: The ZAP by Checkmarx Core project

issue.body:
The "sessions" API view will now return as tokens of a session:

``` XML
 <tokens type="set">
   <token type="set">
     <name>SESSID</name>
     <value>123</value>
     <domain>example.com</domain>
     <path>/</path>
     <secure>false</secure>
   </token>
 </tokens>
```

instead of:

``` XML
 <tokens type="set">
   <SESSID>SESSID=123</SESSID>
 <tokens>
```

preventing exceptions when the name of the session tokens are not valid
XML element names and normalising its structure (no longer dependent on
tokens' names).
Change class HttpSessionsAPI to use a custom ApiResponseSet, to produce
the newer XML structure (class TokenValuesResponseSet), also extract a
method that creates a response with session's data, to reduce code
duplication.
Fix #2246 - Error in sessions view with tokens

issue.title: zap-api-java - ApiResponseElement casting error in constructor of ApiResponseSet (if child is also a set)

repository.name: zaproxy
repository.description: The ZAP by Checkmarx Core project

issue.body:
I am unable to use client.httpSessions.sessions(website, "") method with the zap-api-java client as the xml response which the ZAP API returns contains a set within a set (e.g. for the tokens).

```xml
<sessions type="list">
   <session type="list">
      <name>Session 0</name>
      <tokens type="set">
         <token type="set">
            <name>JSESSIONID</name>
            <value>.....w02</value>
            <domain>.examplesite.com</domain>
            <path>/</path>
            <secure>false</secure>
         </token>
      </tokens>
      <messages_matched>1</messages_matched>
   </session>
</sessions>
```
The ApiResponseSet(Node node) constructor assumes the child is not a set (and tries to cast it to a ApiResponseElement) which then throws a casting exception.
